# Forecast: version must appear in commit messages

The user controls when versions change; see **forecast-version-manual**. When a commit includes changes **they** made to **any** of the following, the **commit message must explicitly state the Forecast app version** (e.g. `v1.9.0` in the subject or first line of the body):

- [`forecast/service-worker.js`](forecast/service-worker.js) — `VERSION` constant (and derived cache names)
- [`forecast/manifest.json`](forecast/manifest.json) — `version` field
- [`forecast/index.html`](forecast/index.html) — `?v=` cache-bust query strings on CSS/JS assets

**Examples (good):**

- `forecast: Enable Radar; release v1.9.0`
- `forecast v1.9.0: radar section, offline cache, README`

**Avoid:** commits that touch those version surfaces without naming the version in the message.

When bumping for a release, the user typically aligns service worker, manifest, and `index.html` `?v=`; mirror that single version in the commit message.
